    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Initially, the term referred to sheets of glass coated with collodion subsequently sensitized and dried. In 1871 Richard Leach Maddox discovered that an emulsion of gelatin containing a sensitive silver salt could be exposed to the action of light in a dry state. This provided a leap forward in photographic media as it simplified the process of taking photographs, avoiding the necessity of plates being prepared immediately before exposure, and processed immediately after.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
